			<tr>
				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: new bard ~ needs grouping advice<a name="33403"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Apr 7 04 2:31 PM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>Anthem is also 10% Haste.  If you have no other haster in the group, skip CoB, and use Anthem.  If you have Haste, use CoB.  When you ding 30, get Amplification.  Amp + Anthem is HUGE STR.  When you sing a song with a haste component, the higher haste wins, but you still get the other buff effects.
<br />

<br />
Your lvl 23 Snare song is also a Slow.  So it is not only useful to snare runners, but throughout the fight, if no one else is Slowing.
<br />

<br />
Your damage songs work best if you swap instruments while you sing them.  While I think instrument twisting is cool, if you want your combat skills maxed, don't use em, except for equipping your Lute for Heal song between fights for added HP regen.  Generally speaking, you are probably better off buffing your group than using your damage songs.  This is true for pretty much all of a Bard's life (grouping life, that is, hehe.  Solo is another matter).
<br />

<br />
As for stats, get all of em except WIS up to 100 at least.  The most significant affect of CHA is NOT mez or charm or even missed notes.  When you Lull a mob, an MR check is done first.  If the mob resists, a second check is made against your CHA to determine if the mob (and often all his friends, hehe) will aggro or not.
<br />

<br />
Once you have your lvl 27 and 28 Charm and Mez songs, the most important thing you can do if charms or mezzes get resisted or break early (MR check for break on every tick), is to have a Wind Instrument equipped when it lands.  The Instrument Modifier will increase the MR debuff component of the song, making the reapplication of your mez easier, and reducing the chance of an early break.  I recommend getting a primary equip flute, so you only have to do ONE click to pop it in, rather than the three clicks it takes to swap into secondary.  Bloodstained Flute is the most affordable, best modifier you will likely get in a primary equippable flute.  (Also, invis song requires a wind instrument, and primary equip is much easier to invis quickly.)
<br />

<br />
Pulling and Crowd Control in LDoNs should ensure that your Defense stays up.  You will certainly get hit often enough, hehe.
<br />

<br />
One thing to consider when shopping for stats, is what buffs will be available to you.  You have CoB for dex, and at lvl 39 you get a song which, when you equip your drum, will peg most folks at 255 easily!  We get lots of STR songs.  We get one CHR song at like lvl 59 or 60, and it's pretty useless, except for helping Divine whatever it is to land on the tank during raids and stuff.  We don't have an STA song.  We don't have HP buff songs.
<br />

<br />
At lower levels, I shopped for AC and HP, with stats as a secondary consideration.  Somone once told me, &quot;The leading cause of death in EQ is lack of HP.&quot;  Again, try to get balanced stats at or above 100.  You may want to focus on a few high CHA items to help with Lull resists (and maybe missed notes... the CHA thing was parsed by some people. There was a difference but the results were not amazing or anything).  I can tell you FOR CERTAIN that CHA affects aggro on resisted Lulls.  If you will pull a lot, CHA is good, mmkay.</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="SmallText"><hr size="1" align="left" width="15%">Scherzo Glissando <BR>
